Certainly! Here is the science quiz for a 4th grader in JSON format:

```json
{
  "quiz": {
    "title": "4th Grade Science Quiz",
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": 1,
        "type": "true_false",
        "question": "Water comes in three states: solid, liquid, and gas.",
        "options": {
          "true": true,
          "false": false
        },
        "answer": "true"
      },
      {
        "id": 2,
        "type": "true_false",
        "question": "The Earth is the center of the Solar System.",
        "options": {
          "true": true,
          "false": false
        },
        "answer": "false"
      },
      {
        "id": 3,
        "type": "multiple_choice",
        "question": "Which of the following are sources of renewable energy? (Choose up to 2)",
        "options": {
          "A": "Coal",
          "B": "Wind",
          "C": "Solar",
          "D": "Oil"
        },
        "answer": ["B", "C"]
      },
      {
        "id": 4,
        "type": "true_false",
        "question": "Plants breathe in oxygen and breathe out carbon dioxide.",
        "options": {
          "true": true,
          "false": false
        },
        "answer": "false"
      },
      {
        "id": 5,
        "type": "multiple_choice",
        "question": "What do plants need to make their own food through photosynthesis? (Choose up to 2)",
        "options": {
          "A": "Sunlight",
          "B": "Water",
          "C": "Dark",
          "D": "Candy"
        },
        "answer": ["A", "B"]
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

In this JSON structure, the quiz object contains a title and a list of questions. Each question is an object with an ID, a type (either "true_false" or "multiple_choice"), the question text, a set of options, and the correct answer(s). For true/false questions, the answer is a string ("true" or "false"), and for multiple-choice questions with multiple correct answers, the answer is an array containing the keys of the correct options.

